<font color="#FF0000">NO SOLDIER SERVES IN VAIN</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug 16  0:02:16 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc,<br><br>
Wars may be a mistake, ideologies may be flawed, but there are some things that are never in question.<br><br>
A true patriot knows that a soldier has never served his country in vain.  To make such a statement shows me your have little respect for the service or life of an American soldier.  Young men served their country faithfully with some making the ultimate sacrifice.<br><br>
No soldier wishes to die for his country only to serve with honor.  We raised our right hand and swore before God to serve.  Takes a special guy to swear before God and honor his promise, don't you think.  Remember integrity and ethics are the backbone of what makes us great.  The disgrace in this process are those who exhibit they have no integrity.<br><br>
Honor and integrity are two of the few things we receive for free in life.  Ours to maintain.  Once given away you can never buy it back for any price.  A sobering thought isn't it.<br><br>
What price do you think these men payed in the many wars fought to allow you the freedom to show such disrespect?<br><br>
Remember these honorable men on a daily basis laid down their lives for them comrades without question.  Some paid the ultimate price and did so without question.  <br><br>
Was it a mistake for the politicians to ask these men to give their lives?  Maybe.  Was their service in vain?  NEVER!!!!!<br><br>
You are right Doc many of us are filled with hate.  You are certainly no exception.  The difference between you and us is at least we don't hate ourselves or our countrymen.<br><br>
Your emotions are displaced.  You ask Cook to forgive all the Vietnamese people.  You weren't there and Doc you show you aren't forgiving for lessor offenses than Cook had to endure.<br><br>
I you didn't have the intestinal fortitude to serve then ZIP your lip.
<p><code>--   (Silent Warrior) </code><p>


